   1import os
   2import json
   3import logging
   4import requests
   5from typing import Optional, List, Any, Dict
   6from .authenticator import PlaidAuthenticator
   7from .logger import logger
   8from . import model
   9
  10
  11def raise_for_status(res: requests.Response) -> None:
  12    if res.status_code >= 400:
  13        try:
  14            content = res.json()
  15        except requests.JSONDecodeError:
  16            content = res.content
  17        raise requests.HTTPError(content, response=res)
  18
  19
  20class PlaidClient:
  21    def __init__(self, base_url: str, authenticator: PlaidAuthenticator) -> None:
  22        self.authenticator = authenticator
  23        self.base_url = base_url
  24        self.session = requests.Session()
  25        self.session.headers["Content-Type"] = "application/json"
  26        self.session.headers["User-Agent"] = "plaid2/python/0.1.0"
  27
  28    def send(
  29        self,
  30        method: str,
  31        url: str,
  32        headers: Dict[str, str],
  33        params: Dict[str, str],
  34        data: Dict[str, Any],
  35    ) -> requests.Response:
  36        self.authenticator.authenticate(headers, params, data)
  37        req = requests.Request(
  38            method=method,
  39            url=url,
  40            headers=headers,
  41            params=params,
  42            json=data,
  43        )
  44        prepped = req.prepare()
  45        do_debug = logger.getEffectiveLevel() == logging.DEBUG
  46        if do_debug:
  47            data = dict(
  48                method=prepped.method,
  49                url=prepped.url,
  50                headers=dict(prepped.headers),
  51            )
  52            if req.json is not None:
  53                data["json"] = req.json
  54            elif type(prepped.body) is bytes:
  55                data["body"] = prepped.body.decode("utf-8")
  56            elif type(prepped.body) is str:
  57                data["body"] = prepped.body
  58            logger.debug(json.dumps(data))
  59        res = self.session.send(prepped)
  60        if do_debug:
  61            data = dict(
  62                status_code=res.status_code,
  63                headers=dict(res.headers),
  64            )
  65            try:
  66                data["json"] = res.json()
  67            except requests.JSONDecodeError:
  68                data["body"] = res.text
  69            logger.debug(json.dumps(data))
  70        raise_for_status(res)
  71        return res
  72
  73    def item_application_list(
  74        self, access_token: Optional[str] = None
  75    ) -> model.ItemApplicationListResponse:
  76        """List a user’s connected applications"""
  77        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
  78        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
  79        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
  80            "access_token": access_token,
  81        }
  82        res = self.send(
  83            "POST", self.base_url + "/item/application/list", headers, params, data
  84        )
  85        data = res.json()
  86        return model.ItemApplicationListResponse.parse_obj(data)

  88    def item_application_scopes_update(
  89        self,
  90        access_token: str,
  91        application_id: str,
  92        scopes: model.Scopes,
  93        context: str,
  94        state: Optional[str] = None,
  95    ) -> model.ItemApplicationScopesUpdateResponse:
  96        """Update the scopes of access for a particular application
  97
  98        Enable consumers to update product access on selected accounts for an application."""
  99        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 100        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 101        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 102            "access_token": access_token,
 103            "application_id": application_id,
 104            "scopes": None if scopes is None else scopes.dict(),
 105            "state": state,
 106            "context": context,
 107        }
 108        res = self.send(
 109            "POST",
 110            self.base_url + "/item/application/scopes/update",
 111            headers,
 112            params,
 113            data,
 114        )
 115        data = res.json()
 116        return model.ItemApplicationScopesUpdateResponse.parse_obj(data)

 148    def auth_get(
 149        self, access_token: str, options: Optional[model.AuthGetRequestOptions] = None
 150    ) -> model.AuthGetResponse:
 151        """Retrieve auth data
 152
 153        The `/auth/get` endpoint returns the bank account and bank identification numbers (such as routing numbers, for US accounts) associated with an Item's checking and savings accounts, along with high-level account data and balances when available.
 154
 155        Note: This request may take some time to complete if `auth` was not specified as an initial product when creating the Item. This is because Plaid must communicate directly with the institution to retrieve the data.
 156
 157        Also note that `/auth/get` will not return data for any new accounts opened after the Item was created. To obtain data for new accounts, create a new Item.
 158
 159        Versioning note: In API version 2017-03-08, the schema of the `numbers` object returned by this endpoint is substantially different. For details, see [Plaid API versioning](https://plaid.com/docs/api/versioning/#version-2018-05-22).
 160
 161        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/auth/#authget>."""
 162        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 163        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 164        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 165            "access_token": access_token,
 166            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 167        }
 168        res = self.send("POST", self.base_url + "/auth/get", headers, params, data)
 169        data = res.json()
 170        return model.AuthGetResponse.parse_obj(data)
 171
 172    def transactions_get(
 173        self,
 174        access_token: str,
 175        start_date: str,
 176        end_date: str,
 177        options: Optional[model.TransactionsGetRequestOptions] = None,
 178    ) -> model.TransactionsGetResponse:
 179        """Get transaction data
 180
 181        The `/transactions/get` endpoint allows developers to receive user-authorized transaction data for credit, depository, and some loan-type accounts (only those with account subtype `student`; coverage may be limited). For transaction history from investments accounts, use the [Investments endpoint](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/investments/) instead. Transaction data is standardized across financial institutions, and in many cases transactions are linked to a clean name, entity type, location, and category. Similarly, account data is standardized and returned with a clean name, number, balance, and other meta information where available.
 182
 183        Transactions are returned in reverse-chronological order, and the sequence of transaction ordering is stable and will not shift.  Transactions are not immutable and can also be removed altogether by the institution; a removed transaction will no longer appear in `/transactions/get`.  For more details, see [Pending and posted transactions](https://plaid.com/docs/transactions/transactions-data/#pending-and-posted-transactions).
 184
 185        Due to the potentially large number of transactions associated with an Item, results are paginated. Manipulate the `count` and `offset` parameters in conjunction with the `total_transactions` response body field to fetch all available transactions.
 186
 187        Data returned by `/transactions/get` will be the data available for the Item as of the most recent successful check for new transactions. Plaid typically checks for new data multiple times a day, but these checks may occur less frequently, such as once a day, depending on the institution. An Item's `status.transactions.last_successful_update` field will show the timestamp of the most recent successful update. To force Plaid to check for new transactions, you can use the `/transactions/refresh` endpoint.
 188
 189        Note that data may not be immediately available to `/transactions/get`. Plaid will begin to prepare transactions data upon Item link, if Link was initialized with `transactions`, or upon the first call to `/transactions/get`, if it wasn't. To be alerted when transaction data is ready to be fetched, listen for the [`INITIAL_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#initial_update) and [`HISTORICAL_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#historical_update) webhooks. If no transaction history is ready when `/transactions/get` is called, it will return a `PRODUCT_NOT_READY` error.
 190
 191        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionsget>."""
 192        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 193        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 194        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 195            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 196            "access_token": access_token,
 197            "start_date": start_date,
 198            "end_date": end_date,
 199        }
 200        res = self.send(
 201            "POST", self.base_url + "/transactions/get", headers, params, data
 202        )
 203        data = res.json()
 204        return model.TransactionsGetResponse.parse_obj(data)
 205
 206    def transactions_refresh(
 207        self, access_token: str
 208    ) -> model.TransactionsRefreshResponse:
 209        """Refresh transaction data
 210
 211        `/transactions/refresh` is an optional endpoint for users of the Transactions product. It initiates an on-demand extraction to fetch the newest transactions for an Item. This on-demand extraction takes place in addition to the periodic extractions that automatically occur multiple times a day for any Transactions-enabled Item. If changes to transactions are discovered after calling `/transactions/refresh`, Plaid will fire a webhook: [`TRANSACTIONS_REMOVED`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactions_removed) will be fired if any removed transactions are detected, and [`DEFAULT_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#default_update) will be fired if any new transactions are detected. New transactions can be fetched by calling `/transactions/get`.
 212
 213        Access to `/transactions/refresh` in Production is specific to certain pricing plans. If you cannot access `/transactions/refresh` in Production, [contact Sales](https://www.plaid.com/contact) for assistance.
 214
 215        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionsrefresh>."""
 216        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 217        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 218        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 219            "access_token": access_token,
 220        }
 221        res = self.send(
 222            "POST", self.base_url + "/transactions/refresh", headers, params, data
 223        )
 224        data = res.json()
 225        return model.TransactionsRefreshResponse.parse_obj(data)
 226
 227    def transactions_recurring_get(
 228        self,
 229        access_token: str,
 230        account_ids: List[str],
 231        options: Optional[model.TransactionsRecurringGetRequestOptions] = None,
 232    ) -> model.TransactionsRecurringGetResponse:
 233        """Fetch recurring transaction streams
 234
 235        The `/transactions/recurring/get` endpoint allows developers to receive a summary of the recurring outflow and inflow streams (expenses and deposits) from a user’s checking, savings or credit card accounts. Additionally, Plaid provides key insights about each recurring stream including the category, merchant, last amount, and more. Developers can use these insights to build tools and experiences that help their users better manage cash flow, monitor subscriptions, reduce spend, and stay on track with bill payments.
 236
 237        This endpoint is not included by default as part of Transactions. To request access to this endpoint and learn more about pricing, contact your Plaid account manager.
 238
 239        Note that unlike `/transactions/get`, `/transactions/recurring/get` will not initialize an Item with Transactions. The Item must already have been initialized with Transactions (either during Link, by specifying it in `/link/token/create`, or after Link, by calling `/transactions/get`) before calling this endpoint. Data is available to `/transactions/recurring/get` approximately 5 seconds after the [`HISTORICAL_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#historical_update) webhook has fired (about 1-2 minutes after initialization).
 240
 241        After the initial call, you can call `/transactions/recurring/get` endpoint at any point in the future to retrieve the latest summary of recurring streams. Since recurring streams do not change often, it will typically not be necessary to call this endpoint more than once per day.
 242
 243        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionsrecurringget>."""
 244        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 245        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 246        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 247            "access_token": access_token,
 248            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 249            "account_ids": account_ids,
 250        }
 251        res = self.send(
 252            "POST", self.base_url + "/transactions/recurring/get", headers, params, data
 253        )
 254        data = res.json()
 255        return model.TransactionsRecurringGetResponse.parse_obj(data)
 256
 257    def transactions_sync(
 258        self,
 259        access_token: str,
 260        cursor: Optional[str] = None,
 261        count: Optional[int] = None,
 262        options: Optional[model.TransactionsSyncRequestOptions] = None,
 263    ) -> model.TransactionsSyncResponse:
 264        """Get incremental transaction updates on an Item
 265
 266        This endpoint replaces `/transactions/get` and its associated webhooks for most common use-cases.
 267
 268        The `/transactions/sync` endpoint allows developers to subscribe to all transactions associated with an Item and get updates synchronously in a stream-like manner, using a cursor to track which updates have already been seen. `/transactions/sync` provides the same functionality as `/transactions/get` and can be used instead of `/transactions/get` to simplify the process of tracking transactions updates.
 269
 270        This endpoint provides user-authorized transaction data for `credit`, `depository`, and some loan-type accounts (only those with account subtype `student`; coverage may be limited). For transaction history from `investments` accounts, use `/investments/transactions/get` instead.
 271
 272        Returned transactions data is grouped into three types of update, indicating whether the transaction was added, removed, or modified since the last call to the API.
 273
 274        In the first call to `/transactions/sync` for an Item, the endpoint will return all historical transactions data associated with that Item up until the time of the API call (as "adds"), which then generates a `next_cursor` for that Item. In subsequent calls, send the `next_cursor` to receive only the changes that have occurred since the previous call.
 275
 276        Due to the potentially large number of transactions associated with an Item, results are paginated. The `has_more` field specifies if additional calls are necessary to fetch all available transaction updates.
 277
 278        Whenever new or updated transaction data becomes available, `/transactions/sync` will provide these updates. Plaid typically checks for new data multiple times a day, but these checks may occur less frequently, such as once a day, depending on the institution. An Item's `status.transactions.last_successful_update` field will show the timestamp of the most recent successful update. To force Plaid to check for new transactions, use the `/transactions/refresh` endpoint.
 279
 280        Note that for newly created Items, data may not be immediately available to `/transactions/sync`. Plaid begins preparing transactions data when the Item is created, but the process can take anywhere from a few seconds to several minutes to complete, depending on the number of transactions available.
 281
 282        To be alerted when new data is available, listen for the [`SYNC_UPDATES_AVAILABLE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#sync_updates_available) webhook.
 283
 284        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionssync>."""
 285        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 286        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 287        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 288            "access_token": access_token,
 289            "cursor": cursor,
 290            "count": count,
 291            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 292        }
 293        res = self.send(
 294            "POST", self.base_url + "/transactions/sync", headers, params, data
 295        )
 296        data = res.json()
 297        return model.TransactionsSyncResponse.parse_obj(data)
 298
 299    def institutions_get(
 300        self,
 301        count: int,
 302        offset: int,
 303        country_codes: List[str],
 304        options: Optional[model.InstitutionsGetRequestOptions] = None,
 305    ) -> model.InstitutionsGetResponse:
 306        """Get details of all supported institutions
 307
 308        Returns a JSON response containing details on all financial institutions currently supported by Plaid. Because Plaid supports thousands of institutions, results are paginated.
 309
 310        If there is no overlap between an institution’s enabled products and a client’s enabled products, then the institution will be filtered out from the response. As a result, the number of institutions returned may not match the count specified in the call.
 311
 312        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/institutions/#institutionsget>."""
 313        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 314        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 315        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 316            "count": count,
 317            "offset": offset,
 318            "country_codes": country_codes,
 319            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 320        }
 321        res = self.send(
 322            "POST", self.base_url + "/institutions/get", headers, params, data
 323        )
 324        data = res.json()
 325        return model.InstitutionsGetResponse.parse_obj(data)

The `public_key` parameter has since been deprecated; all customers are encouraged to use `client_id` and `secret` instead.

 341        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/institutions/#institutionssearch>."""
 342        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 343        params: Dict[str, str] = {}

 347            "country_codes": country_codes,
 348            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 349        }
 350        res = self.send(
 351            "POST", self.base_url + "/institutions/search", headers, params, data
 352        )
 353        data = res.json()
 354        return model.InstitutionsSearchResponse.parse_obj(data)

 356    def institutions_get_by_id(
 357        self,
 358        institution_id: str,
 359        country_codes: List[str],
 360        options: Optional[model.InstitutionsGetByIdRequestOptions] = None,
 361    ) -> model.InstitutionsGetByIdResponse:
 362        """Get details of an institution
 363
 364        Returns a JSON response containing details on a specified financial institution currently supported by Plaid.
 365
 366        Versioning note: API versions 2019-05-29 and earlier allow use of the `public_key` parameter instead of the `client_id` and `secret` to authenticate to this endpoint. The `public_key` has been deprecated; all customers are encouraged to use `client_id` and `secret` instead.
 367
 368
 369        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/institutions/#institutionsget_by_id>."""
 370        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 371        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 372        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 373            "institution_id": institution_id,
 374            "country_codes": country_codes,
 375            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 376        }
 377        res = self.send(
 378            "POST", self.base_url + "/institutions/get_by_id", headers, params, data

 383    def item_remove(self, access_token: str) -> model.ItemRemoveResponse:
 384        """Remove an Item
 385
 386        The `/item/remove` endpoint allows you to remove an Item. Once removed, the `access_token`, as well as any processor tokens or bank account tokens associated with the Item, is no longer valid and cannot be used to access any data that was associated with the Item.
 387
 388        Note that in the Development environment, issuing an `/item/remove`  request will not decrement your live credential count. To increase your credential account in Development, contact Support.
 389
 390        Also note that for certain OAuth-based institutions, an Item removed via `/item/remove` may still show as an active connection in the institution's OAuth permission manager.
 391
 392        API versions 2019-05-29 and earlier return a `removed` boolean as part of the response.
 393
 394        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/items/#itemremove>."""
 395        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 396        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 397        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 398            "access_token": access_token,
 399        }
 400        res = self.send("POST", self.base_url + "/item/remove", headers, params, data)
 401        data = res.json()
 402        return model.ItemRemoveResponse.parse_obj(data)

 404    def accounts_get(
 405        self,
 406        access_token: str,
 407        options: Optional[model.AccountsGetRequestOptions] = None,
 408    ) -> model.AccountsGetResponse:
 409        """Retrieve accounts
 410
 411        The `/accounts/get` endpoint can be used to retrieve a list of accounts associated with any linked Item. Plaid will only return active bank accounts — that is, accounts that are not closed and are capable of carrying a balance.
 412        For items that went through the updated account selection pane, this endpoint only returns accounts that were permissioned by the user when they initially created the Item. If a user creates a new account after the initial link, you can capture this event through the [`NEW_ACCOUNTS_AVAILABLE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/items/#new_accounts_available) webhook and then use Link's [update mode](https://plaid.com/docs/link/update-mode/) to request that the user share this new account with you.
 413
 414        This endpoint retrieves cached information, rather than extracting fresh information from the institution. As a result, balances returned may not be up-to-date; for realtime balance information, use `/accounts/balance/get` instead. Note that some information is nullable.
 415
 416        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/accounts/#accountsget>."""
 417        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 418        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 419        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 420            "access_token": access_token,
 421            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 422        }
 423        res = self.send("POST", self.base_url + "/accounts/get", headers, params, data)
 424        data = res.json()
 425        return model.AccountsGetResponse.parse_obj(data)

 504

 506

 510
 511        `RECURRING_TRANSACTIONS_UPDATE`: Recurring Transactions webhook to be fired for a given Sandbox Item. If the Item does not support Recurring Transactions, a `SANDBOX_PRODUCT_NOT_ENABLED` error will result.
 512
 513        Note that this endpoint is provided for developer ease-of-use and is not required for testing webhooks; webhooks will also fire in Sandbox under the same conditions that they would in Production or Development.
 514
 515        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/sandbox/#sandboxitemfire_webhook>."""
 516        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 517        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 518        data: Dict[str, Any] = {

 522        }
 523        res = self.send(

 525        )

 661        res = self.send(
 662            "POST",
 663            self.base_url + "/identity_verification/create",
 664            headers,
 665            params,

1460        The `/liabilities/get` endpoint returns various details about an Item with loan or credit accounts. Liabilities data is available primarily for US financial institutions, with some limited coverage of Canadian institutions. Currently supported account types are account type `credit` with account subtype `credit card` or `paypal`, and account type `loan` with account subtype `student` or `mortgage`. To limit accounts listed in Link to types and subtypes supported by Liabilities, you can use the `account_filters` parameter when [creating a Link token](https://plaid.com/docs/api/tokens/#linktokencreate).
1461
1462        The types of information returned by Liabilities can include balances and due dates, loan terms, and account details such as original loan amount and guarantor. Data is refreshed approximately once per day; the latest data can be retrieved by calling `/liabilities/get`.
1463
1464        Note: This request may take some time to complete if `liabilities` was not specified as an initial product when creating the Item. This is because Plaid must communicate directly with the institution to retrieve the additional data.
1465
1466        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/liabilities/#liabilitiesget>."""
1467        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
1468        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
1469        data: Dict[str, Any] = {

1471            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
1472        }

1474            "POST", self.base_url + "/liabilities/get", headers, params, data
1475        )

1489
1490        The endpoint is idempotent: if a developer has already made a request with the same payment details, Plaid will return the same `recipient_id`.
1491
1492
1493        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/payment-initiation/#payment_initiationrecipientcreate>."""
1494        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
1495        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
1496        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
1497            "name": name,
1498            "iban": iban,
1499            "bacs": None if bacs is None else bacs.dict(),
1500            "address": None if address is None else address.dict(),
1501        }
1502        res = self.send(
1503            "POST",
1504            self.base_url + "/payment_initiation/recipient/create",
1505            headers,
1506            params,
1507            data,
1508        )
1509        data = res.json()
1510        return model.PaymentInitiationRecipientCreateResponse.parse_obj(data)

1584    def payment_initiation_payment_create(
1585        self,
1586        recipient_id: str,
1587        reference: str,
1588        amount: model.PaymentAmount,
1589        schedule: Optional[model.ExternalPaymentScheduleRequest] = None,
1590        options: Optional[model.ExternalPaymentOptions] = None,
1591    ) -> model.PaymentInitiationPaymentCreateResponse:
1592        """Create a payment
1593
1594        After creating a payment recipient, you can use the `/payment_initiation/payment/create` endpoint to create a payment to that recipient.  Payments can be one-time or standing order (recurring) and can be denominated in either EUR or GBP.  If making domestic GBP-denominated payments, your recipient must have been created with BACS numbers. In general, EUR-denominated payments will be sent via SEPA Credit Transfer and GBP-denominated payments will be sent via the Faster Payments network, but the payment network used will be determined by the institution. Payments sent via Faster Payments will typically arrive immediately, while payments sent via SEPA Credit Transfer will typically arrive in one business day.
1595
1596        Standing orders (recurring payments) must be denominated in GBP and can only be sent to recipients in the UK. Once created, standing order payments cannot be modified or canceled via the API. An end user can cancel or modify a standing order directly on their banking application or website, or by contacting the bank. Standing orders will follow the payment rules of the underlying rails (Faster Payments in UK). Payments can be sent Monday to Friday, excluding bank holidays. If the pre-arranged date falls on a weekend or bank holiday, the payment is made on the next working day. It is not possible to guarantee the exact time the payment will reach the recipient’s account, although at least 90% of standing order payments are sent by 6am.
1597
1598        In the Development environment, payments must be below 5 GBP / EUR. For details on any payment limits in Production, contact your Plaid Account Manager.
1599
1600        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/payment-initiation/#payment_initiationpaymentcreate>."""
1601        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
1602        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
1603        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
1604            "recipient_id": recipient_id,
1605            "reference": reference,
1606            "amount": None if amount is None else amount.dict(),
1607            "schedule": None if schedule is None else schedule.dict(),
1608            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
1609        }
1610        res = self.send(
1611            "POST",
1612            self.base_url + "/payment_initiation/payment/create",
1613            headers,
1614            params,
1615            data,
1616        )
1617        data = res.json()
1618        return model.PaymentInitiationPaymentCreateResponse.parse_obj(data)
1619

1943    def asset_report_refresh(
1944        self,
1945        asset_report_token: str,
1946        days_requested: Optional[int] = None,
1947        options: Optional[model.AssetReportRefreshRequestOptions] = None,
1948    ) -> model.AssetReportRefreshResponse:
1949        """Refresh an Asset Report
1950
1951        An Asset Report is an immutable snapshot of a user's assets. In order to "refresh" an Asset Report you created previously, you can use the `/asset_report/refresh` endpoint to create a new Asset Report based on the old one, but with the most recent data available.
1952
1953        The new Asset Report will contain the same Items as the original Report, as well as the same filters applied by any call to `/asset_report/filter`. By default, the new Asset Report will also use the same parameters you submitted with your original `/asset_report/create` request, but the original `days_requested` value and the values of any parameters in the `options` object can be overridden with new values. To change these arguments, simply supply new values for them in your request to `/asset_report/refresh`. Submit an empty string ("") for any previously-populated fields you would like set as empty.
1954
1955        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/assets/#asset_reportrefresh>."""
1956        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
1957        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
1958        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
1959            "asset_report_token": asset_report_token,
1960            "days_requested": days_requested,
1961            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
1962        }
1963        res = self.send(
1964            "POST", self.base_url + "/asset_report/refresh", headers, params, data
1965        )
1966        data = res.json()
1967        return model.AssetReportRefreshResponse.parse_obj(data)

1995

2010    def asset_report_filter(
2011        self, asset_report_token: str, account_ids_to_exclude: List[str]
2012    ) -> model.AssetReportFilterResponse:
2013        """Filter Asset Report
2014
2015        By default, an Asset Report will contain all of the accounts on a given Item. In some cases, you may not want the Asset Report to contain all accounts. For example, you might have the end user choose which accounts are relevant in Link using the Account Select view, which you can enable in the dashboard. Or, you might always exclude certain account types or subtypes, which you can identify by using the `/accounts/get` endpoint. To narrow an Asset Report to only a subset of accounts, use the `/asset_report/filter` endpoint.
2016
2017        To exclude certain Accounts from an Asset Report, first use the `/asset_report/create` endpoint to create the report, then send the `asset_report_token` along with a list of `account_ids` to exclude to the `/asset_report/filter` endpoint, to create a new Asset Report which contains only a subset of the original Asset Report's data.
2018
2019        Because Asset Reports are immutable, calling `/asset_report/filter` does not alter the original Asset Report in any way; rather, `/asset_report/filter` creates a new Asset Report with a new token and id. Asset Reports created via `/asset_report/filter` do not contain new Asset data, and are not billed.
2020
2021        Plaid will fire a [`PRODUCT_READY`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/assets/#product_ready) webhook once generation of the filtered Asset Report has completed.
2022
2023        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/assets/#asset_reportfilter>."""
2024        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
2025        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
2026        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
2027            "asset_report_token": asset_report_token,
2028            "account_ids_to_exclude": account_ids_to_exclude,
2029        }
2030        res = self.send(
2031            "POST", self.base_url + "/asset_report/filter", headers, params, data
2032        )
2033        data = res.json()
2034        return model.AssetReportFilterResponse.parse_obj(data)

2045
2046        By default, an Asset Report includes transaction descriptions as returned by the bank, as opposed to parsed and categorized by Plaid. You can also receive cleaned and categorized transactions, as well as additional insights like merchant name or location information. We call this an Asset Report with Insights. 2047

2056            "fast_report": fast_report,
2057        }
2058        res = self.send(
2059            "POST", self.base_url + "/asset_report/get", headers, params, data

2567    def transfer_authorization_create(
2568        self,
2569        type_: str,
2570        network: str,
2571        amount: str,
2572        ach_class: str,
2573        user: model.TransferAuthorizationUserInRequest,
2574        access_token: Optional[str] = None,
2575        account_id: Optional[str] = None,
2576        device: Optional[model.TransferAuthorizationDevice] = None,
2577        origination_account_id: Optional[str] = None,
2578        iso_currency_code: Optional[str] = None,
2579        user_present: Optional[bool] = None,
2580        payment_profile_id: Optional[str] = None,
2581    ) -> model.TransferAuthorizationCreateResponse:
2582        """Create a transfer authorization
2583
2584        Use the `/transfer/authorization/create` endpoint to determine transfer failure risk.
2585
2586        In Plaid's sandbox environment the decisions will be returned as follows:
2587
2588          - To approve a transfer with null rationale code, make an authorization request with an `amount` less than the available balance in the account.
2589
2590          - To approve a transfer with the rationale code `MANUALLY_VERIFIED_ITEM`, create an Item in Link through the [Same Day Micro-deposits flow](https://plaid.com/docs/auth/coverage/testing/#testing-same-day-micro-deposits).
2591
2592          - To approve a transfer with the rationale code `LOGIN_REQUIRED`, [reset the login for an Item](https://plaid.com/docs/sandbox/#item_login_required).
2593
2594          - To decline a transfer with the rationale code `NSF`, the available balance on the account must be less than the authorization `amount`. See [Create Sandbox test data](https://plaid.com/docs/sandbox/user-custom/) for details on how to customize data in Sandbox.
2595
2596          - To decline a transfer with the rationale code `RISK`, the available balance on the account must be exactly $0. See [Create Sandbox test data](https://plaid.com/docs/sandbox/user-custom/) for details on how to customize data in Sandbox.
2597
2598        For guaranteed ACH customers, the following fields are required : `user.phone_number` (optional if `email_address` provided), `user.email_address` (optional if `phone_number` provided), `device.ip_address`, `device.user_agent`, and `user_present`.
2599
2600        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transfer/#transferauthorizationcreate>."""
2601        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
2602        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
2603        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
2604            "access_token": access_token,
2605            "account_id": account_id,
2606            "type": type,
2607            "network": network,
2608            "amount": amount,
2609            "ach_class": ach_class,
2610            "user": None if user is None else user.dict(),
2611            "device": None if device is None else device.dict(),
2612            "origination_account_id": origination_account_id,
2613            "iso_currency_code": iso_currency_code,
2614            "user_present": user_present,
2615            "payment_profile_id": payment_profile_id,
2616        }
2617        res = self.send(
2618            "POST",
2619            self.base_url + "/transfer/authorization/create",
2620            headers,
2621            params,
2622            data,
2623        )
2624        data = res.json()
2625        return model.TransferAuthorizationCreateResponse.parse_obj(data)

4334    @classmethod
4335    def from_env(cls) -> "PlaidClient":
4336        env = os.environ["PLAID_ENV"]
4337        url = f"https://{env}.plaid.com"
4338        return cls(base_url=url, authenticator=PlaidAuthenticator.from_env())
def raise_for_status(res: requests.models.Response) -> None: 
12def raise_for_status(res: requests.Response) -> None:
13    if res.status_code >= 400:
14        try:
15            content = res.json()
16        except requests.JSONDecodeError:
17            content = res.content
18        raise requests.HTTPError(content, response=res)
class PlaidClient: 
  21class PlaidClient:
  22    def __init__(self, base_url: str, authenticator: PlaidAuthenticator) -> None:
  23        self.authenticator = authenticator
  24        self.base_url = base_url
  25        self.session = requests.Session()
  26        self.session.headers["Content-Type"] = "application/json"
  27        self.session.headers["User-Agent"] = "plaid2/python/0.1.0"
  28
  29    def send(
  30        self,
  31        method: str,
  32        url: str,
  33        headers: Dict[str, str],
  34        params: Dict[str, str],
  35        data: Dict[str, Any],
  36    ) -> requests.Response:
  37        self.authenticator.authenticate(headers, params, data)
  38        req = requests.Request(
  39            method=method,
  40            url=url,
  41            headers=headers,
  42            params=params,
  43            json=data,
  44        )
  45        prepped = req.prepare()
  46        do_debug = logger.getEffectiveLevel() == logging.DEBUG
  47        if do_debug:
  48            data = dict(
  49                method=prepped.method,
  50                url=prepped.url,
  51                headers=dict(prepped.headers),
  52            )
  53            if req.json is not None:
  54                data["json"] = req.json
  55            elif type(prepped.body) is bytes:
  56                data["body"] = prepped.body.decode("utf-8")
  57            elif type(prepped.body) is str:
  58                data["body"] = prepped.body
  59            logger.debug(json.dumps(data))
  60        res = self.session.send(prepped)
  61        if do_debug:
  62            data = dict(
  63                status_code=res.status_code,
  64                headers=dict(res.headers),
  65            )
  66            try:
  67                data["json"] = res.json()
  68            except requests.JSONDecodeError:
  69                data["body"] = res.text
  70            logger.debug(json.dumps(data))
  71        raise_for_status(res)
  72        return res
  73

 149    def auth_get(
 150        self, access_token: str, options: Optional[model.AuthGetRequestOptions] = None
 151    ) -> model.AuthGetResponse:
 152        """Retrieve auth data
 153
 154        The `/auth/get` endpoint returns the bank account and bank identification numbers (such as routing numbers, for US accounts) associated with an Item's checking and savings accounts, along with high-level account data and balances when available.
 155
 156        Note: This request may take some time to complete if `auth` was not specified as an initial product when creating the Item. This is because Plaid must communicate directly with the institution to retrieve the data.
 157
 158        Also note that `/auth/get` will not return data for any new accounts opened after the Item was created. To obtain data for new accounts, create a new Item.
 159
 160        Versioning note: In API version 2017-03-08, the schema of the `numbers` object returned by this endpoint is substantially different. For details, see [Plaid API versioning](https://plaid.com/docs/api/versioning/#version-2018-05-22).
 161
 162        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/auth/#authget>."""
 163        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 164        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 165        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 166            "access_token": access_token,
 167            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 168        }
 169        res = self.send("POST", self.base_url + "/auth/get", headers, params, data)
 170        data = res.json()
 171        return model.AuthGetResponse.parse_obj(data)

 173    def transactions_get(
 174        self,
 175        access_token: str,
 176        start_date: str,
 177        end_date: str,
 178        options: Optional[model.TransactionsGetRequestOptions] = None,
 179    ) -> model.TransactionsGetResponse:
 180        """Get transaction data
 181
 182        The `/transactions/get` endpoint allows developers to receive user-authorized transaction data for credit, depository, and some loan-type accounts (only those with account subtype `student`; coverage may be limited). For transaction history from investments accounts, use the [Investments endpoint](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/investments/) instead. Transaction data is standardized across financial institutions, and in many cases transactions are linked to a clean name, entity type, location, and category. Similarly, account data is standardized and returned with a clean name, number, balance, and other meta information where available.
 183
 184        Transactions are returned in reverse-chronological order, and the sequence of transaction ordering is stable and will not shift.  Transactions are not immutable and can also be removed altogether by the institution; a removed transaction will no longer appear in `/transactions/get`.  For more details, see [Pending and posted transactions](https://plaid.com/docs/transactions/transactions-data/#pending-and-posted-transactions).
 185
 186        Due to the potentially large number of transactions associated with an Item, results are paginated. Manipulate the `count` and `offset` parameters in conjunction with the `total_transactions` response body field to fetch all available transactions.
 187
 188        Data returned by `/transactions/get` will be the data available for the Item as of the most recent successful check for new transactions. Plaid typically checks for new data multiple times a day, but these checks may occur less frequently, such as once a day, depending on the institution. An Item's `status.transactions.last_successful_update` field will show the timestamp of the most recent successful update. To force Plaid to check for new transactions, you can use the `/transactions/refresh` endpoint.
 189
 190        Note that data may not be immediately available to `/transactions/get`. Plaid will begin to prepare transactions data upon Item link, if Link was initialized with `transactions`, or upon the first call to `/transactions/get`, if it wasn't. To be alerted when transaction data is ready to be fetched, listen for the [`INITIAL_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#initial_update) and [`HISTORICAL_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#historical_update) webhooks. If no transaction history is ready when `/transactions/get` is called, it will return a `PRODUCT_NOT_READY` error.
 191
 192        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionsget>."""
 193        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 194        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 195        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 196            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 197            "access_token": access_token,
 198            "start_date": start_date,
 199            "end_date": end_date,
 200        }
 201        res = self.send(
 202            "POST", self.base_url + "/transactions/get", headers, params, data
 203        )
 204        data = res.json()
 205        return model.TransactionsGetResponse.parse_obj(data)
 206
 207    def transactions_refresh(
 208        self, access_token: str
 209    ) -> model.TransactionsRefreshResponse:
 210        """Refresh transaction data
 211
 212        `/transactions/refresh` is an optional endpoint for users of the Transactions product. It initiates an on-demand extraction to fetch the newest transactions for an Item. This on-demand extraction takes place in addition to the periodic extractions that automatically occur multiple times a day for any Transactions-enabled Item. If changes to transactions are discovered after calling `/transactions/refresh`, Plaid will fire a webhook: [`TRANSACTIONS_REMOVED`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactions_removed) will be fired if any removed transactions are detected, and [`DEFAULT_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#default_update) will be fired if any new transactions are detected. New transactions can be fetched by calling `/transactions/get`.
 213
 214        Access to `/transactions/refresh` in Production is specific to certain pricing plans. If you cannot access `/transactions/refresh` in Production, [contact Sales](https://www.plaid.com/contact) for assistance.
 215
 216        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionsrefresh>."""
 217        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 218        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 219        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 220            "access_token": access_token,
 221        }
 222        res = self.send(
 223            "POST", self.base_url + "/transactions/refresh", headers, params, data
 224        )
 225        data = res.json()
 226        return model.TransactionsRefreshResponse.parse_obj(data)
 227
 228    def transactions_recurring_get(
 229        self,
 230        access_token: str,
 231        account_ids: List[str],
 232        options: Optional[model.TransactionsRecurringGetRequestOptions] = None,
 233    ) -> model.TransactionsRecurringGetResponse:
 234        """Fetch recurring transaction streams
 235
 236        The `/transactions/recurring/get` endpoint allows developers to receive a summary of the recurring outflow and inflow streams (expenses and deposits) from a user’s checking, savings or credit card accounts. Additionally, Plaid provides key insights about each recurring stream including the category, merchant, last amount, and more. Developers can use these insights to build tools and experiences that help their users better manage cash flow, monitor subscriptions, reduce spend, and stay on track with bill payments.
 237
 238        This endpoint is not included by default as part of Transactions. To request access to this endpoint and learn more about pricing, contact your Plaid account manager.
 239
 240        Note that unlike `/transactions/get`, `/transactions/recurring/get` will not initialize an Item with Transactions. The Item must already have been initialized with Transactions (either during Link, by specifying it in `/link/token/create`, or after Link, by calling `/transactions/get`) before calling this endpoint. Data is available to `/transactions/recurring/get` approximately 5 seconds after the [`HISTORICAL_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#historical_update) webhook has fired (about 1-2 minutes after initialization).
 241
 242        After the initial call, you can call `/transactions/recurring/get` endpoint at any point in the future to retrieve the latest summary of recurring streams. Since recurring streams do not change often, it will typically not be necessary to call this endpoint more than once per day.
 243
 244        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionsrecurringget>."""
 245        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 246        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 247        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 248            "access_token": access_token,
 249            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 250            "account_ids": account_ids,
 251        }
 252        res = self.send(
 253            "POST", self.base_url + "/transactions/recurring/get", headers, params, data
 254        )
 255        data = res.json()
 256        return model.TransactionsRecurringGetResponse.parse_obj(data)
 257
 258    def transactions_sync(
 259        self,
 260        access_token: str,
 261        cursor: Optional[str] = None,
 262        count: Optional[int] = None,
 263        options: Optional[model.TransactionsSyncRequestOptions] = None,
 264    ) -> model.TransactionsSyncResponse:
 265        """Get incremental transaction updates on an Item
 266
 267        This endpoint replaces `/transactions/get` and its associated webhooks for most common use-cases.
 268
 269        The `/transactions/sync` endpoint allows developers to subscribe to all transactions associated with an Item and get updates synchronously in a stream-like manner, using a cursor to track which updates have already been seen. `/transactions/sync` provides the same functionality as `/transactions/get` and can be used instead of `/transactions/get` to simplify the process of tracking transactions updates.
 270
 271        This endpoint provides user-authorized transaction data for `credit`, `depository`, and some loan-type accounts (only those with account subtype `student`; coverage may be limited). For transaction history from `investments` accounts, use `/investments/transactions/get` instead.
 272
 273        Returned transactions data is grouped into three types of update, indicating whether the transaction was added, removed, or modified since the last call to the API.
 274
 275        In the first call to `/transactions/sync` for an Item, the endpoint will return all historical transactions data associated with that Item up until the time of the API call (as "adds"), which then generates a `next_cursor` for that Item. In subsequent calls, send the `next_cursor` to receive only the changes that have occurred since the previous call.
 276
 277        Due to the potentially large number of transactions associated with an Item, results are paginated. The `has_more` field specifies if additional calls are necessary to fetch all available transaction updates.
 278
 279        Whenever new or updated transaction data becomes available, `/transactions/sync` will provide these updates. Plaid typically checks for new data multiple times a day, but these checks may occur less frequently, such as once a day, depending on the institution. An Item's `status.transactions.last_successful_update` field will show the timestamp of the most recent successful update. To force Plaid to check for new transactions, use the `/transactions/refresh` endpoint.
 280
 281        Note that for newly created Items, data may not be immediately available to `/transactions/sync`. Plaid begins preparing transactions data when the Item is created, but the process can take anywhere from a few seconds to several minutes to complete, depending on the number of transactions available.
 282
 283        To be alerted when new data is available, listen for the [`SYNC_UPDATES_AVAILABLE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#sync_updates_available) webhook.
 284
 285        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionssync>."""
 286        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 287        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 288        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 289            "access_token": access_token,
 290            "cursor": cursor,
 291            "count": count,
 292            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 293        }
 294        res = self.send(
 295            "POST", self.base_url + "/transactions/sync", headers, params, data
 296        )
 297        data = res.json()
 298        return model.TransactionsSyncResponse.parse_obj(data)
 299

1585    def payment_initiation_payment_create(
1586        self,
1587        recipient_id: str,
1588        reference: str,
1589        amount: model.PaymentAmount,
1590        schedule: Optional[model.ExternalPaymentScheduleRequest] = None,
1591        options: Optional[model.ExternalPaymentOptions] = None,
1592    ) -> model.PaymentInitiationPaymentCreateResponse:
1593        """Create a payment
1594
1595        After creating a payment recipient, you can use the `/payment_initiation/payment/create` endpoint to create a payment to that recipient.  Payments can be one-time or standing order (recurring) and can be denominated in either EUR or GBP.  If making domestic GBP-denominated payments, your recipient must have been created with BACS numbers. In general, EUR-denominated payments will be sent via SEPA Credit Transfer and GBP-denominated payments will be sent via the Faster Payments network, but the payment network used will be determined by the institution. Payments sent via Faster Payments will typically arrive immediately, while payments sent via SEPA Credit Transfer will typically arrive in one business day.
1596
1597        Standing orders (recurring payments) must be denominated in GBP and can only be sent to recipients in the UK. Once created, standing order payments cannot be modified or canceled via the API. An end user can cancel or modify a standing order directly on their banking application or website, or by contacting the bank. Standing orders will follow the payment rules of the underlying rails (Faster Payments in UK). Payments can be sent Monday to Friday, excluding bank holidays. If the pre-arranged date falls on a weekend or bank holiday, the payment is made on the next working day. It is not possible to guarantee the exact time the payment will reach the recipient’s account, although at least 90% of standing order payments are sent by 6am.
1598
1599        In the Development environment, payments must be below 5 GBP / EUR. For details on any payment limits in Production, contact your Plaid Account Manager.
1600
1601        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/payment-initiation/#payment_initiationpaymentcreate>."""
1602        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
1603        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
1604        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
1605            "recipient_id": recipient_id,
1606            "reference": reference,
1607            "amount": None if amount is None else amount.dict(),
1608            "schedule": None if schedule is None else schedule.dict(),
1609            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
1610        }
1611        res = self.send(
1612            "POST",
1613            self.base_url + "/payment_initiation/payment/create",
1614            headers,
1615            params,
1616            data,
1617        )
1618        data = res.json()
1619        return model.PaymentInitiationPaymentCreateResponse.parse_obj(data)
1620

1823    def item_create_public_token(
1824        self, access_token: str
1825    ) -> model.ItemPublicTokenCreateResponse:
1826        """Create public token
1827
1828        Note: As of July 2020, the `/item/public_token/create` endpoint is deprecated. Instead, use `/link/token/create` with an `access_token` to create a Link token for use with [update mode](https://plaid.com/docs/link/update-mode).
1829
1830        If you need your user to take action to restore or resolve an error associated with an Item, generate a public token with the `/item/public_token/create` endpoint and then initialize Link with that `public_token`.
1831
1832        A `public_token` is one-time use and expires after 30 minutes. You use a `public_token` to initialize Link in [update mode](https://plaid.com/docs/link/update-mode) for a particular Item. You can generate a `public_token` for an Item even if you did not use Link to create the Item originally.
1833
1834        The `/item/public_token/create` endpoint is **not** used to create your initial `public_token`. If you have not already received an `access_token` for a specific Item, use Link to obtain your `public_token` instead. See the [Quickstart](https://plaid.com/docs/quickstart) for more information.
1835
1836        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/tokens/#itempublic_tokencreate>."""
1837        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
1838        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
1839        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
1840            "access_token": access_token,
1841        }
1842        res = self.send(
1843            "POST", self.base_url + "/item/public_token/create", headers, params, data
1844        )
1845        data = res.json()
1846        return model.ItemPublicTokenCreateResponse.parse_obj(data)

1916    def asset_report_create(
1917        self,

1921    ) -> model.AssetReportCreateResponse:

1925
1926        The Asset Report takes some time to be created and is not available immediately after calling `/asset_report/create`. For full details of the webhook schema, see [Asset Report webhooks](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/assets/#webhooks).
1927
1928        The `/asset_report/create` endpoint creates an Asset Report at a moment in time. Asset Reports are immutable. To get an updated Asset Report, use the `/asset_report/refresh` endpoint.
1929
1930        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/assets/#asset_reportcreate>."""
1931        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
1932        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
1933        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
1934            "access_tokens": access_tokens,
1935            "days_requested": days_requested,
1936            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
1937        }
1938        res = self.send(
1939            "POST", self.base_url + "/asset_report/create", headers, params, data
1940        )
1941        data = res.json()
1942        return model.AssetReportCreateResponse.parse_obj(data)

1944    def asset_report_refresh(
1945        self,
1946        asset_report_token: str,
1947        days_requested: Optional[int] = None,
1948        options: Optional[model.AssetReportRefreshRequestOptions] = None,
1949    ) -> model.AssetReportRefreshResponse:
1950        """Refresh an Asset Report
1951
1952        An Asset Report is an immutable snapshot of a user's assets. In order to "refresh" an Asset Report you created previously, you can use the `/asset_report/refresh` endpoint to create a new Asset Report based on the old one, but with the most recent data available.
1953
1954        The new Asset Report will contain the same Items as the original Report, as well as the same filters applied by any call to `/asset_report/filter`. By default, the new Asset Report will also use the same parameters you submitted with your original `/asset_report/create` request, but the original `days_requested` value and the values of any parameters in the `options` object can be overridden with new values. To change these arguments, simply supply new values for them in your request to `/asset_report/refresh`. Submit an empty string ("") for any previously-populated fields you would like set as empty.
1955
1956        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/assets/#asset_reportrefresh>."""
1957        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
1958        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
1959        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
1960            "asset_report_token": asset_report_token,
1961            "days_requested": days_requested,
1962            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
1963        }
1964        res = self.send(
1965            "POST", self.base_url + "/asset_report/refresh", headers, params, data
1966        )
1967        data = res.json()
1968        return model.AssetReportRefreshResponse.parse_obj(data)
1969

2011    def asset_report_filter(
2012        self, asset_report_token: str, account_ids_to_exclude: List[str]
2013    ) -> model.AssetReportFilterResponse:
2014        """Filter Asset Report
2015
2016        By default, an Asset Report will contain all of the accounts on a given Item. In some cases, you may not want the Asset Report to contain all accounts. For example, you might have the end user choose which accounts are relevant in Link using the Account Select view, which you can enable in the dashboard. Or, you might always exclude certain account types or subtypes, which you can identify by using the `/accounts/get` endpoint. To narrow an Asset Report to only a subset of accounts, use the `/asset_report/filter` endpoint.
2017
2018        To exclude certain Accounts from an Asset Report, first use the `/asset_report/create` endpoint to create the report, then send the `asset_report_token` along with a list of `account_ids` to exclude to the `/asset_report/filter` endpoint, to create a new Asset Report which contains only a subset of the original Asset Report's data.
2019
2020        Because Asset Reports are immutable, calling `/asset_report/filter` does not alter the original Asset Report in any way; rather, `/asset_report/filter` creates a new Asset Report with a new token and id. Asset Reports created via `/asset_report/filter` do not contain new Asset data, and are not billed.
2021
2022        Plaid will fire a [`PRODUCT_READY`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/assets/#product_ready) webhook once generation of the filtered Asset Report has completed.
2023
2024        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/assets/#asset_reportfilter>."""
2025        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
2026        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
2027        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
2028            "asset_report_token": asset_report_token,
2029            "account_ids_to_exclude": account_ids_to_exclude,
2030        }
2031        res = self.send(
2032            "POST", self.base_url + "/asset_report/filter", headers, params, data
2033        )
2034        data = res.json()
2035        return model.AssetReportFilterResponse.parse_obj(data)

Before calling `/asset_report/get`, you must first create the Asset Report using `/asset_report/create` (or filter an Asset Report using `/asset_report/filter`) and then wait for the [`PRODUCT_READY`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/assets/#product_ready) webhook to fire, indicating that the Report is ready to be retrieved.
2046
2047        By default, an Asset Report includes transaction descriptions as returned by the bank, as opposed to parsed and categorized by Plaid. You can also receive cleaned and categorized transactions, as well as additional insights like merchant name or location information. We call this an Asset Report with Insights. An Asset Report with Insights provides transaction category, location, and merchant information in addition to the transaction strings provided in a standard Asset Report.
2048
2049        To retrieve an Asset Report with Insights, call the `/asset_report/get` endpoint with `include_insights` set to `true`.
2050
2051        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/assets/#asset_reportget>."""
2052        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
2053        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
2054        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
2055            "asset_report_token": asset_report_token,
2056            "include_insights": include_insights,
2057            "fast_report": fast_report,
2058        }
2059        res = self.send(
2060            "POST", self.base_url + "/asset_report/get", headers, params, data
2061        )
2062        data = res.json()
2063        return model.AssetReportGetResponse.parse_obj(data)

2568    def transfer_authorization_create(
2569        self,
2570        type_: str,
2571        network: str,
2572        amount: str,
2573        ach_class: str,
2574        user: model.TransferAuthorizationUserInRequest,
2575        access_token: Optional[str] = None,
2576        account_id: Optional[str] = None,
2577        device: Optional[model.TransferAuthorizationDevice] = None,
2578        origination_account_id: Optional[str] = None,
2579        iso_currency_code: Optional[str] = None,
2580        user_present: Optional[bool] = None,
2581        payment_profile_id: Optional[str] = None,
2582    ) -> model.TransferAuthorizationCreateResponse:
2583        """Create a transfer authorization
2584
2585        Use the `/transfer/authorization/create` endpoint to determine transfer failure risk.
2586
2587        In Plaid's sandbox environment the decisions will be returned as follows:
2588
2589          - To approve a transfer with null rationale code, make an authorization request with an `amount` less than the available balance in the account.
2590
2591          - To approve a transfer with the rationale code `MANUALLY_VERIFIED_ITEM`, create an Item in Link through the [Same Day Micro-deposits flow](https://plaid.com/docs/auth/coverage/testing/#testing-same-day-micro-deposits).
2592
2593          - To approve a transfer with the rationale code `LOGIN_REQUIRED`, [reset the login for an Item](https://plaid.com/docs/sandbox/#item_login_required).
2594
2595          - To decline a transfer with the rationale code `NSF`, the available balance on the account must be less than the authorization `amount`. See [Create Sandbox test data](https://plaid.com/docs/sandbox/user-custom/) for details on how to customize data in Sandbox.
2596
2597          - To decline a transfer with the rationale code `RISK`, the available balance on the account must be exactly $0. See [Create Sandbox test data](https://plaid.com/docs/sandbox/user-custom/) for details on how to customize data in Sandbox.
2598
2599        For guaranteed ACH customers, the following fields are required : `user.phone_number` (optional if `email_address` provided), `user.email_address` (optional if `phone_number` provided), `device.ip_address`, `device.user_agent`, and `user_present`.
2600
2601        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transfer/#transferauthorizationcreate>."""
2602        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
2603        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
2604        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
2605            "access_token": access_token,
2606            "account_id": account_id,
2607            "type": type,
2608            "network": network,
2609            "amount": amount,
2610            "ach_class": ach_class,
2611            "user": None if user is None else user.dict(),
2612            "device": None if device is None else device.dict(),
2613            "origination_account_id": origination_account_id,
2614            "iso_currency_code": iso_currency_code,
2615            "user_present": user_present,
2616            "payment_profile_id": payment_profile_id,
2617        }
2618        res = self.send(
2619            "POST",
2620            self.base_url + "/transfer/authorization/create",

3591        }

4336    def from_env(cls) -> "PlaidClient":
4337        env = os.environ["PLAID_ENV"]
4338        url = f"https://{env}.plaid.com"
4339        return cls(base_url=url, authenticator=PlaidAuthenticator.from_env())
PlaidClient( base_url: str, authenticator: plaid2.authenticator.PlaidAuthenticator) 
22    def __init__(self, base_url: str, authenticator: PlaidAuthenticator) -> None:
23        self.authenticator = authenticator
24        self.base_url = base_url
25        self.session = requests.Session()
26        self.session.headers["Content-Type"] = "application/json"
27        self.session.headers["User-Agent"] = "plaid2/python/0.1.0"
def send( self, method: str, url: str, headers: Dict[str, str], params: Dict[str, str], data: Dict[str, Any]) -> requests.models.Response: 
29    def send(
30        self,
31        method: str,
32        url: str,
33        headers: Dict[str, str],
34        params: Dict[str, str],
35        data: Dict[str, Any],
36    ) -> requests.Response:
37        self.authenticator.authenticate(headers, params, data)
38        req = requests.Request(
39            method=method,
40            url=url,
41            headers=headers,
42            params=params,
43            json=data,
44        )
45        prepped = req.prepare()
46        do_debug = logger.getEffectiveLevel() == logging.DEBUG
47        if do_debug:
48            data = dict(
49                method=prepped.method,
50                url=prepped.url,
51                headers=dict(prepped.headers),
52            )
53            if req.json is not None:
54                data["json"] = req.json
55            elif type(prepped.body) is bytes:
56                data["body"] = prepped.body.decode("utf-8")
57            elif type(prepped.body) is str:
58                data["body"] = prepped.body
59            logger.debug(json.dumps(data))
60        res = self.session.send(prepped)
61        if do_debug:
62            data = dict(
63                status_code=res.status_code,
64                headers=dict(res.headers),
65            )
66            try:
67                data["json"] = res.json()
68            except requests.JSONDecodeError:
69                data["body"] = res.text
70            logger.debug(json.dumps(data))
71        raise_for_status(res)
72        return res

def transactions_get( self, access_token: str, start_date: str, end_date: str, options: Optional[plaid2.model.transactions_get_request_options.TransactionsGetRequestOptions] = None) -> plaid2.model.transactions_get_response.TransactionsGetResponse: 
173    def transactions_get(
174        self,
175        access_token: str,
176        start_date: str,
177        end_date: str,
178        options: Optional[model.TransactionsGetRequestOptions] = None,
179    ) -> model.TransactionsGetResponse:
180        """Get transaction data
181
182        The `/transactions/get` endpoint allows developers to receive user-authorized transaction data for credit, depository, and some loan-type accounts (only those with account subtype `student`; coverage may be limited). For transaction history from investments accounts, use the [Investments endpoint](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/investments/) instead. Transaction data is standardized across financial institutions, and in many cases transactions are linked to a clean name, entity type, location, and category. Similarly, account data is standardized and returned with a clean name, number, balance, and other meta information where available.
183
184        Transactions are returned in reverse-chronological order, and the sequence of transaction ordering is stable and will not shift.  Transactions are not immutable and can also be removed altogether by the institution; a removed transaction will no longer appear in `/transactions/get`.  For more details, see [Pending and posted transactions](https://plaid.com/docs/transactions/transactions-data/#pending-and-posted-transactions).
185
186        Due to the potentially large number of transactions associated with an Item, results are paginated. Manipulate the `count` and `offset` parameters in conjunction with the `total_transactions` response body field to fetch all available transactions.
187
188        Data returned by `/transactions/get` will be the data available for the Item as of the most recent successful check for new transactions. Plaid typically checks for new data multiple times a day, but these checks may occur less frequently, such as once a day, depending on the institution. An Item's `status.transactions.last_successful_update` field will show the timestamp of the most recent successful update. To force Plaid to check for new transactions, you can use the `/transactions/refresh` endpoint.
189
190        Note that data may not be immediately available to `/transactions/get`. Plaid will begin to prepare transactions data upon Item link, if Link was initialized with `transactions`, or upon the first call to `/transactions/get`, if it wasn't. To be alerted when transaction data is ready to be fetched, listen for the [`INITIAL_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#initial_update) and [`HISTORICAL_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#historical_update) webhooks. If no transaction history is ready when `/transactions/get` is called, it will return a `PRODUCT_NOT_READY` error.
191
192        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionsget>."""
193        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
194        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
195        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
196            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
197            "access_token": access_token,
198            "start_date": start_date,
199            "end_date": end_date,
200        }
201        res = self.send(
202            "POST", self.base_url + "/transactions/get", headers, params, data
203        )
204        data = res.json()
205        return model.TransactionsGetResponse.parse_obj(data)

Get transaction data

The /transactions/get endpoint allows developers to receive user-authorized transaction data for credit, depository, and some loan-type accounts (only those with account subtype student; coverage may be limited). For transaction history from investments accounts, use the Investments endpoint instead. Transaction data is standardized across financial institutions, and in many cases transactions are linked to a clean name, entity type, location, and category. Similarly, account data is standardized and returned with a clean name, number, balance, and other meta information where available.

Transactions are returned in reverse-chronological order, and the sequence of transaction ordering is stable and will not shift. Transactions are not immutable and can also be removed altogether by the institution; a removed transaction will no longer appear in /transactions/get. For more details, see Pending and posted transactions.

Due to the potentially large number of transactions associated with an Item, results are paginated. Manipulate the count and offset parameters in conjunction with the total_transactions response body field to fetch all available transactions.

Data returned by /transactions/get will be the data available for the Item as of the most recent successful check for new transactions. Plaid typically checks for new data multiple times a day, but these checks may occur less frequently, such as once a day, depending on the institution. An Item's status.transactions.last_successful_update field will show the timestamp of the most recent successful update. To force Plaid to check for new transactions, you can use the /transactions/refresh endpoint.

Note that data may not be immediately available to /transactions/get. Plaid will begin to prepare transactions data upon Item link, if Link was initialized with transactions, or upon the first call to /transactions/get, if it wasn't. To be alerted when transaction data is ready to be fetched, listen for the INITIAL_UPDATE and HISTORICAL_UPDATE webhooks. If no transaction history is ready when /transactions/get is called, it will return a PRODUCT_NOT_READY error.

See endpoint docs at https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionsget.

def transactions_refresh( self, access_token: str) -> plaid2.model.transactions_refresh_response.TransactionsRefreshResponse:

208        self, access_token: str

210        """Refresh transaction data
211
212        `/transactions/refresh` is an optional endpoint for users of the Transactions product. It initiates an on-demand extraction to fetch the newest transactions for an Item. This on-demand extraction takes place in addition to the periodic extractions that automatically occur multiple times a day for any Transactions-enabled Item. If changes to transactions are discovered after calling `/transactions/refresh`, Plaid will fire a webhook: [`TRANSACTIONS_REMOVED`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactions_removed) will be fired if any removed transactions are detected, and [`DEFAULT_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#default_update) will be fired if any new transactions are detected. New transactions can be fetched by calling `/transactions/get`.
213
214        Access to `/transactions/refresh` in Production is specific to certain pricing plans. If you cannot access `/transactions/refresh` in Production, [contact Sales](https://www.plaid.com/contact) for assistance.
215
216        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionsrefresh>."""
217        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
218        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
219        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
220            "access_token": access_token,
221        }
222        res = self.send(
223            "POST", self.base_url + "/transactions/refresh", headers, params, data
224        )
225        data = res.json()
226        return model.TransactionsRefreshResponse.parse_obj(data)
